3. Conduits: The Controlled Communication Channels

3.1 Conduit Types

Conduit Between Zones Direction Protocol Max Rate
C0 Zone 0 → Zone 1 Unidirectional Memory-Mapped FIFO 100 kHz
C1 Zone 1 → Zone 2 Bidirectional (limited) SPI / UART / Ethernet 1 MHz
C2 Zone 1 → Zone 3 Unidirectional Serial / Display 115.2 kbps

3.2 Conduit Rules (Hardware-Enforced)

Rule 1: No Reverse Path into Zone 0

· Zone 1 has write access to Zone 0's memory-mapped output register.
· Zone 1 has no read access to Zone 0's internal state (ROM, SRAM, FSM).
· This is enforced at the hardware level (memory controller).

Rule 2: Watchdog on Every Conduit

· Each conduit has a hardware watchdog timer.
· If Zone 1 does not read from Zone 0's FIFO within a bounded interval (e.g., 10 ms), the watchdog asserts a fail-safe.
· Fail-safe action: Zone 1 sets all outputs to a known-safe state (e.g., 0V / 0% output).

Rule 3: Rate-Limiting

· Zone 1 cannot poll Zone 0 faster than the FIFO can produce.
· Attempts to exceed the rate are silently dropped (no overflow).

Rule 4: Encryption for SRAM Updates

· Zone 0 SRAM updates (SK-1024 protocol) are encrypted.
· The key is stored in hardware (e.g., TPM, eFuse).
· Zone 1 cannot initiate updates—only the National Authority can.

